posts.name: Mert Ata BABER
posts.cooked: I’ve seen the other network switch recommendations posts but non of the given are avaliable in Turkey. So, I found switches below but not sure If they would work in FRC. I am open to other switch suggestions. https://www.tp-link.com/en/business-networking/litewave-switch/ls1005g/

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked: One concern I’d have with the zyxel switch is that since it has QOS built in, there’s a chance it may interfere with the data being transferred. I’d look for switches with less smarts.

posts.name: Mert Ata BABER
posts.cooked: Are you reffering to zyxel one or tp-link one?

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked: That was in reference to the zyxel one. Didn’t notice the second link. The tplink one looks reasonable to me.

posts.name: gartaud
posts.cooked:
We have been using the D-Link GO-SW-5G for years because it’s super cheap and very light.

D-Link GO-SW-5G Go 5-Port Gigabit Easy masaüstü switch (10/100/1000 MBit/s, otomatik MDI/Mdix tanıma) Beyaz : Amazon.com.tr: Bilgisayar

It needs to be connected to a VRM to get 5V supply.

posts.name: Mert Ata BABER
posts.cooked: I will message them as there is no info of shipping time etc. on website. Thanks.

posts.name: Robert
posts.cooked: I’m a fan of ZebraSwitch myself. The TPLink switch available from FIRST Choice is also a solid option, and you can even pop the top off and put the voltage regulator inside of it, making it even more compact.

link_counts.title: ZebraSwitch - Reliable Robot Ethernet that won't break your BOM

posts.name: Mert Ata BABER
posts.cooked: Awesome, I found first choice one for real cheap at a local seller. I will definitely look into it. Thanks.

posts.name: Mert Ata BABER
posts.cooked: Do you know If we can power it via 5v 500mA or should we put add an extra voltage converter to VRM?

posts.name: Joe Ross
posts.cooked: The power adapter that comes with it is 5v 600mA. You may be able to get away with the VRM 500mA port, but it would be better to use the 5v 2A  port.

posts.name: Mert Ata BABER
posts.cooked: Can we directly connect it to 2A port or should we add something to step it down 0.6A range? Tplink support said they didn’t know if would fry it or not.

posts.name: Robert
posts.cooked: The 2A port will be adequate. The only circumstances under which it will draw more than 600mA is if there is an electrical short, in which case you have much bigger problems.
